description:
Bug 38131ajc needs -d option. I am using 1.1rc1. This is a regression since rc1 and a deviation from javac. I am guessing this may have something to do with a change in the underlying Eclipse compiler.

Steps to reproduce:
1. Create a class in a subpackage such as:
   package subpackage;

   public class Test {
      public static void main(String[] args) {
         System.out.println("Hello");
      }
   }
2. Compile using the following command:
   ajc subpackage\Test.java

Observed Behavior:
After executing the above command, a directory named "subpackage" is created under the existing "subpackage" directory. The compiled class file (Test.class) is placed inside the "subpackage\subpackage" directory.

Running the java command results in the following exception:
Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: subpackage/Test.

Expected Behavior:
The compiled Test.class file should be put directly in the "subpackage" directory.

Suggested Resolution:
Adding the "-d ." option to the ajc command resolves the issue.

Steps to reproduce (updated):
1. Create a class in a subpackage such as:
   package subpackage;

   public class Test {
      public static void main(String[] args) {
         System.out.println("Hello");
      }
   }
2. Compile using the following command:
   ajc -d . subpackage\Test.java
